		<div class="container">
			<h2>Just where did our kelp go?</h2>

			<p class="content offset">
				At the turn of the century, the Santa Monica Bay hosted over 
				40,000 acres of kelp forest, and the diverse sea life that it supported.
			</p>

			<p class="content offset">
				Around that time, the demand for sea otter pelts brought them to near elimination.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="container">
			<h2>The disrupted food chain.</h2>
			<p class="content offset">
				Sea otters eat urchins. Urchins eat kelp. 
				When the sea otters disappeared, this allowed the urchin population 
				to flourish, and over time they decimated 95% of our local kelp forests.
			</p>
		</div>
	
		<div class="container gap">
		</div>
		
